# /etc/wyrd/custodian.env — configuration for wyrd-custodian.service.
# Mirrors the M4 blueprint's B.5 invocation (docs/design/architecture/
# m4-first-deployment-blueprint.md).
#
# WARNING: run exactly ONE custodian per cluster. Single-active is NOT enforced
# against a distributed metadata store until the etcd Coordination backend (#365);
# a second custodian would reconcile concurrently.
#
#   --metadata-backend fdb   REQUIRED in production: the CLI defaults to the
#                            dev-only embedded redb store, which would silently
#                            reconcile a DIFFERENT metadata store than the
#                            gateways. FoundationDB is the production backend
#                            (ADR-0042); it reads WYRD_FDB_CLUSTER_FILE below.
#   --zone                   the fenced zone name this custodian maintains.
#   --endpoints/--ids/--failure-domains
#                            the WHOLE operator-wired D-server fleet, aligned
#                            one-per-endpoint. GC defers while any listed server
#                            is unreachable, so keep this list exact. The default
#                            durability is RS(6,3) — 9 fragments per chunk — so a
#                            real fleet is at least 9 D servers in 9 INDEPENDENT
#                            failure domains (see the gateway example's warning).
#   --otlp-endpoint          where durability telemetry leaves the process.
#
# Optional: --gc-expired-pending arms GC's expired-pending sweep — UNSAFE while
# any writer runs against this backend (see `wyrd custodian` usage, #557).
#
# NOTE: no --coordination-backend here, deliberately. The custodian does not
# take one — it campaigns through process-local coordination only, which is WHY
# run-exactly-one is on the operator until etcd fencing lands (#365). Passing
# the flag would be silently ignored and imply a fencing that is not active.
WYRD_CUSTODIAN_ARGS=--zone zone-a --metadata-backend fdb --endpoints http://10.0.1.d0:50051,http://10.0.1.d1:50051,http://10.0.1.d2:50051,http://10.0.1.d3:50051,http://10.0.1.d4:50051,http://10.0.1.d5:50051,http://10.0.1.d6:50051,http://10.0.1.d7:50051,http://10.0.1.d8:50051 --ids 0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8 --failure-domains fd0,fd1,fd2,fd3,fd4,fd5,fd6,fd7,fd8 --otlp-endpoint http://10.0.1.o0:4317

# The FDB cluster file fdbcli wrote at cluster bring-up — distribute it to each
# host; the fdb client rewrites it on coordinator changes (unit grants the path).
WYRD_FDB_CLUSTER_FILE=/etc/foundationdb/fdb.cluster
